#DESCRIPTION
#KEYWORDS('integrals', 'fundamental theorem of calculus')
# Integrals - Fundamental theorem of calculus:  \int_x^{10} t^3dt
#ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl");

TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a1=random(3,8,1);
$b1=random(5,12,1);

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
If  \( \displaystyle f(x) = \int_x^{$b1} t^$a1 dt \) $PAR
then
$BR
\( f'(x) = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}
EOT
$ans1="-x^$a1";

&ANS(function_cmp($ans1));

&SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));

$SOL $BR $BR

The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, part I, can be found on p.392 of your
textbook.  It says that if
\[ g(x) = \int_a^x f(t) dt \]
then the derivative of \(g(x)\) with respect to \(x\), written
\(\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\) or \(g'(x)\), is equal to \(f(x)\).  $PAR

Applying that in this particular circumstance, we find
\[
\begin{align*}
f'(x)	&= \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_x^{$b1} t^{$a1} dt \right)	\\\\
	&= \frac{d}{dx} \left( - \int_{$b1}^x t^{$a1} dt \right)	\\\\
	&= - \frac{d}{dx} \left( \int_{$b1}^x t^{$a1} dt \right)	\\\\
	&= - x^{$a1}
\end{align*}
\]

EOT

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.

